\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}
Let $J(t)$ be a current operator.  
The current--current response function is obtained by Fourier transforming the correlation:
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{JJ}(\omega)
=
\int
dt\,
e^{i\omega t}
\langle J(t)J(0)\rangle .
\end{equation}

The transport coefficient is then extracted from the dissipative part of that correlator:
\begin{equation}
\boxed{
\sigma(\omega)
=
\frac{1}{\omega}
\operatorname{Im}\Pi_{JJ}(\omega).
}
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Interpretation.}
Transport coefficients arise from quantum current correlations rather than from purely classical response laws.
